"Written evidence from Which [PUB0019]\n&#xa0;\nPublic Administration Select Committee (PASC)The citizen and public services: issues and questions&#xa0;&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nSummary of key points&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nMeasures to support consumer choice&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nMeasures to promote consumer voice&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nA single public services ombudsman&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nUser-triggered inspections&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nSuper complaints in public services&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nKey features of super complaints \n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nBoth of these resulted in a market study.\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nWhen Healthwatch England provides this information and advice to the CQC, the Secretary of State, the NHS Commissioning Board, Monitor or local authorities, they are obliged under the Act to inform Healthwatch in writing of their response or proposed response to the advice, although there is no limit on the amount of time these bodies have to respond and no guidance on how they must consider whether or not to take action.\n \nIt is too early to know how Healthwatch will use these powers, but it is conceivable that they could be used as a form of super complaint to any of these bodies.\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nDecember 2013\nAppendix: Consumer views on public services&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;&#xa0;\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;Figures come from the Which? \nConsumer Insight Tracker\n, September 2013\n&#xa0;Populus, on behalf of Which?, interviewed a representative sample of \n210\n6\n \nUK adults online between 13th and 15th September. \n&#xa0;\n \nData were weighted to be demographically representative of all UK adults. \n&#xa0;\nAll percentages are just based on those who have experience of using this service. All base sizes are above 800 respondents. \nPopulus is a member of the British Polling Council and abides by its rules\n.\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n See: \nThe Student Academic Experience Survey\n, Which?, May 2013; \nInvestigation: GPs\n, Which? Magazine, April 2013; \nInvestigation: Home Care\n, Which? Magazine, October 2012; \nCare \nHomes I\nnvestigated\n, Which? Magazine, May 2011\n Which? carried out qualitative hall tests in September 2010 involving 30 minute depth interviews with adults in Lichfield and Watford who had experience of GP and hospital care in the last 12 months.\n \nThe Student Academic Experience Survey\n, Which?, May 2013\n \nPopulus,\n&#xa0;\non\n&#xa0;\nbehalf\n&#xa0;\nof\n&#xa0;\nWhich?, interviewed a random sample\n&#xa0;\nof\n&#xa0;\n2,101 UK adults aged 18+ online between 3rd and \n6th May 2013\n \nWhich? \nConsumer Insight Tracker\n, September 2013. For further details see appendix.\n For example in social care, if users want to ensure that their complaint is considered for quality improvem\nent purposes, they could be ex\np\nec\nted to report their concerns to up to five different bodies: the provider, the local authority, the Local Government Ombudsman (LGO), the CQC and local Healthwatch. \n \nPopulus,\n&#xa0;\non\n&#xa0;\nbehalf\n&#xa0;\nof\n&#xa0;\nWhich?, interviewed a random sample\n&#xa0;\nof\n&#xa0;\n2,101 UK adults aged 18+ online between 3rd and \n6th May 2013\n In July, Ofsted carried out 719 unscheduled inspections of providers that had been prompted by a complaint a 509 per cent increase since September 2012 when just 118 unscheduled inspections were carried out. During this time the number of providers given a lower rating following the complaint-driven inspection also rose significantly with 234 receiving a lower judgement in July, compared with 37 in September last year.\n"